article.headline: Longhorns lose rebounding battle, but win game
article.story:
AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Dominating defense. Thirty points off
turnovers. Call it another comfortable home win -- at least
statistically -- for Texas (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP).

Still, Wednesday night's 67-45 win over Oklahoma State didn't
sit well with Longhorns coach Jody Conradt. Texas struggled to find
its rhythm on offense and was outrebounded, 31-27, for the third
time this season.

"We had tempo issues tonight," Conradt said. "It's not good
when we get outrebounded. We'd play hard for a while, then somebody
would relax."

Guard Jamie Carey provided the offense for the Longhorns with 18
points on 7-of-13 shooting, including four 3-pointers.

"You definitely want the ball in the hands of someone who's
hot," Carey said. "You have to be able to know the difference
between a good shot and a bad shot. We're learning."

Stacy Stephens added 13 points, and Tiffany Jackson scored 10 for
Texas (16-2, 4-1 Big 12), which ran its home winning streak to 29
games.

Texas stifled the Cowgirls with a suffocating defense that
forced 27 turnovers. The Longhorns challenged the Oklahoma State
guards on the perimeter and worked to deny every entry pass to center Trisha Skibbe.

Skibbe scored 12 points, well below her average of 21.3. The
Cowgirls (6-10, 1-4) have lost four in a row.

"Texas did a good job of really jamming her and forcing her out
of her comfort zone in the lane," said Oklahoma State coach Julie
Goodenough. "Turnovers really did us in tonight. When you give up
30 points on your own turnovers ... it's hard to keep up."

The frenetic play on defense led to some quick baskets, but the
Longhorns forced up some bad shots when they settled into their
halfcourt sets. Texas shot 46 percent as a team but missed several
open looks at the basket.

"One of the hardest things to do is play frantic on defense,
which we want to do, and then slow it down on offense," Conradt
said. "We have to show we can dig in and we have to shoot
better."

Oklahoma State, which lost by 50 points to Oklahoma four days
earlier, kept it close in the first half.

Texas led 25-20 late in the half before Carey and Jackson scored
all of the Longhorns' points in a 9-4 run that opened a 34-24 lead.

Heather Schreiber began the second half with a 3-pointer.
Stephens hit a layup and Carey made another 3 from deep in the left
corner in a 8-0 Texas run that made it 42-24. The Longhorns led by
at least 15 points the rest of the way.
